==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mew
<hw>Mew</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<?/w</ets>,
akin to D. <ets>meeuw</ets>, G. <ets>m⟦oum⟧we</ets>, OHG.
<ets>m<?/h</ets>, Icel. <ets>m⟦amac⟧r</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>A gull, esp. the common British species (<spn>Larus canus</spn>);
called also <altname>sea mew</altname>, <altname>maa</altname>,
<altname>mar</altname>, <altname>mow</altname>, and
<altname>cobb</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mew
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mewed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mewing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>muen</ets>, F.
<ets>muer</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mutare</ets> to change, fr.
<ets>movere</ets> to move. See <er>Move</er>, and cf. <er>Mew</er> a
cage, <er>Molt</er>.]</ety> <def>To shed or cast; to change; to molt;
<as>as, the hawk <ex>mewed</ex> his feathers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nine times the moon had <qex>mewed</qex> her horns.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mew
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cast the feathers; to molt;
hence, to change; to put on a new appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now everything doth <qex>mew</qex>,⟦br⟧
And shifts his rustic winter robe.</q>
<rj><qau>Turbervile.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mew
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mue</ets>, F. <ets>mue</ets>
change of feathers, scales, skin, the time or place when the change
occurs, fr. <ets>muer</ets> to molt, mew, L. <ets>mutare</ets> to
change. See 2d <er>Mew</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A cage for hawks while mewing; a coop for fattening
fowls; hence, any inclosure; a place of confinement or shelter; -- in
the latter sense usually in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full many a fat partrich had he in <qex>mewe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forthcoming from her darksome <qex>mew</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Violets in their secret <qex>mews</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stable or range of stables for horses; -- compound
used in the plural, and so called from the royal stables in London,
built on the site of the king's mews for hawks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mew
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mew</er> a cage.]</ety>
<def>To shut up; to inclose; to confine, as in a cage or other
inclosure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>More pity that the eagle should be <qex>mewed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Close <qex>mewed</qex> in their sedans, for fear of air.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Mew
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Of imitative origin; cf. G.
<ets>miauen</ets>.]</ety> <def>To cry as a cat.</def> <altsp>[Written
also <asp>meaw</asp>, <asp>meow</asp>.]</altsp>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Mew
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The common cry of a cat.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mewl</ent>⟦br⟧
